[[File:John Aitchison (British Army officer), Kensal Green Cemetery 03.JPG|thumb|Kensal Green Cemetery mausoleum]]

[[General]] '''Sir John Aitchison''' [[Order of the Bath|GCB]] (25 April 1779 - 12 May 1875) was a [[British Army]] officer.

==Military career==
Aitchison was commissioned at 16 into the [[Scots Guards|3rd Regiment of Foot Guards]], later to be the Scots Guards. He took part in the crossing of the [[Douro|River Douro]] during the [[Peninsular War]].<ref name=mmt>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmtrust.org.uk/mausolea/view/266/Aitchison_Mausoleum|title=Aitchison Mausoleum|publisher=The Mausolea & Monuments Trust|accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref> He fought at the [[Battle of Talavera]] in July 1809, the [[Battle of Bussaco]] in September 1810 and the [[Battle of Salamanca]] in July 1812 before seeing action at the [[Battle of Vitoria]] in June 1813, the [[Siege of San Sebasti√°n]] in July 1813 and the [[Battle of Nivelle]] in November 1813.<ref name=mmt/> He also fought at the [[Battle of the Nive]] in December 1813 and [[Battle of Bayonne]] in April 1814 and went on to become [[Major General]] on the staff of the [[Madras Presidency]] in 1845.<ref name=mmt/> 

He was colonel of the [[72nd Regiment, Duke of Albany's Own Highlanders]] from 1851 to 1870 and of the [[Scots Fusilier Guards]] from 1870 to his death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishempire.co.uk/forces/armyunits/britishinfantry/scotsguards.htm|title=the Third Regiment of Foot Guards|publisher=British Empire|accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref> He was promoted full general on 30 July 1860.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=22416|page=3123|date=24 August 1860}}</ref>

He died in 1875 and was buried at [[Kensal Green Cemetery]] in a mausoleum west of the main chapel.<ref name=mmt/> He had married Ellen Elizabeth and had one son, Archibald John Aitchison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p30160.htm|title=Sir John Aitchison|publisher=The Peerage.com|accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref>

